Machine Learning¶

In [61]:
dfscaled = df.iloc[:,1:7].apply(zscore) 

## Removing mpg because it is the target variable, 
## Removing origin as it is a categorical variable
## Removing year as it should ideally not have any impact on either mpg or the clustering and it is also a categorical variable
In [62]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters = range(1,10)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    model.fit(dfscaled)
    prediction = model.predict(dfscaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(dfscaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis = 1))/dfscaled.shape[0])

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average Distortion')
plt.title('Selecting K with elbow method');
We see that the ideal number of clusters is coming out to be either 2 or 4 with the elbow method¶
In [63]:

The number of clusters suggested by the dendrogram is 2, just like the K-means clustering exercise.¶

Insights:¶

  1. K means clustersing is a faster algorithm compared to the hierarchical clustering
  1. The number of clusters can be found out with the elbow plot or silhouette method in K means, for Agglomerative, one has to look at the dendrogram to determine the number of clusters and sometimes it may be difficult to pick. (although sometimes it gets difficult to pick a K for K means as well)
  1. The challenge with K means can be the initiation. Based on the first few points chosen the clusters may be slightly different. Therefore reproducibility can be a challenge. Results are reproducable in hierarchical clustering

  1. SUVs
  2. Hatchbacks or small size cars

Question:¶

How using different models for different clusters will be helpful in this case and how it will be different than using one single model without clustering? Mention how it impacts performance and prediction.

Answer:¶

In different clusters different models can be used to fit the data. We can also look at different algorithms to see what fits the data the best.

In this scenario, we see that linear regression does not perform very well on the data. However, other algorithms can be applied to the different clusters to improve results

If each cluster has enough data to train the model, then performance and prediction would in most cases go up. However, an alternative to this can be using a non linear model

Suggestions or Improvements¶

  1. Quality of data can be improved. For example some data points for the column hp were missing. We add bias when we perform data imputation

  2. Quantity of data also needs to improve. 398 data points are not enough to fit a model especially when we are looking at clustering and fitting a different model for each cluster

  3. There are no concerns around variety, velocity or veracity of the data
